See cross-references section for a full description of the sources. The isolines of the USGS contour map were interpolated using the Topogrid function of ArcInfo. The contour lines were used as the interpolation value. A gridsize of 105 feet was used. The commands used were as follows. topogrid h2o-g 125 contour bdrk-clip CONTOUR datatype contour end The grid was contoured at one-foot intervals to create a more detailed contour of the groundwater elevation beneath Denver. The following command was used to contour. GROUNDWATER-1 = CONTOUR(H2O-G, INTERVAL, 1, #)</complete>   </dataqual>   <spdoinfo>     <direct>Vector</direct>     <ptvctinf>       <sdtsterm>         <sdtstype>String</sdtstype>         <ptvctcnt>11166</ptvctcnt>       </sdtsterm>     </ptvctinf>   </spdoinfo>   <spref>     <horizsys>       <geograph>         <latres>8.9831528411952133e-009</latres>         <longres>8.9831528411952133e-009</longres>         <geogunit>Decimal Degrees</geogunit>       </geograph>       <geodetic>         <horizdn>D WGS 1984</horizdn>         <ellips>WGS 1984</ellips>         <semiaxis>6378137.0</semiaxis>         <denflat>298.257223563</denflat>       </geodetic>     </horizsys>   </spref>   <eainfo>     <detailed>       <enttyp>         <enttypl>groundwater_one_foot_contours___1996</enttypl>       </enttyp>       <attr>         <attrlabl>OBJECTID</attrlabl>         <attrdef>Internal feature number.</attrdef>         <attrdefs>ESRI</attrdefs>         <attrdomv>           <udom>Sequential unique whole numbers that are automatically generated.</udom>         </attrdomv>       </attr>       <attr>         <attrlabl>CONTOUR</attrlabl>         <attrdef>Contour interval in feet above sea level;
